We can’t live as an avoidant species. We are peak White Noise; numbing ourselves with the excess of modern life during toxic events that are apocalyptic to whole towns and states. The Ohio train derailment is on the verge of being the biggest ecological disaster in US history, and the media have barely said a word.
Over 1M pounds of vinyl chloride were on this train. Now, the EPA has confirmed it has entered the Ohio River, which is home to 25M people.
Never forget how we got here:
In 2018, the Association of American Railroads spent $4,737,989, and Norfolk Southern spent $1,025,330, lobbying to reverse the Obama-era ECP brake safety rule that was designed to prevent disasters like this.
The Trump administration reversed it.
This story out of Ohio seems to be suppressed by the media. How can a disaster of this magnitude not be the "Top" story?
Ohio has ~75,000 farms, 90% are run by families or individuals. They rank 1st in production of Swiss cheese, 2nd in egg production, 3rd in tomatoes & pumpkins, 5th in bell pepper yield, 6th in sweet corn & cucumbers, & 8th in chickens sold.
If you don't know why what's going on in East Palestine, OH is significant you should probably Google it. That red dot at the top part of the Ohio River Basin is where the disaster is happening and filtering into the water supply.

#EastPalestineOH #NorfolkSouthern #OhioChernobyl #OhioChemicalDisaster
#climate #gretathunberg #ohio #midwest #whitenoise #avoidant 

Finally, check the last slide. The toxic gas released by this controlled destruction (Burning) of these tankers is the same gas used during World War one and can be deadly.

“Southern relics, shelves lined with canned and pickled foods, a bronze statue of a Black Madonna and child, and the improvisational gospel music of his band, the Black Monks, encapsulate Theaster Gates Jr.’s memories of childhood summers in Mississippi. To create The Double Wide, the artist salvaged old materials from far-flung places, including fragments from a barn in Indiana and pine flooring from New York’s Park Avenue Armory. When put together, these materials represent an experience of dislocation. The artist creates a space for our physical and spiritual senses that preserves and summons the tastes, feelings, and sounds of the South.
Although Gates grew up in Chicago, he often traveled to see his family in Humphreys County, Mississippi. He distinetly recalls his uncle’s double-wide trailer, which served as a candy store by day and a juke joint by night. The work captures the sweetness, joy, and sacredness that exist not only as a memory but as a real place for joining the past and the present.”

@brooklynmuseum @theastergates

Let's not kid ourselves. I am optimistic about the potential of AI and data analytics to transform the food industry, but we must not ignore the potential job displacement that may result. It is important to embrace these new technologies while also preparing for the future of work. The World Economic Forum estimates that AI could displace approximately 85 million jobs globally by 2025, and I have been monitoring this trend in the food industry and other sectors for several years just before my work in using AI was featured in an article in MIT @technologyreview. The pace of displacement is now faster than ever before, and I am concerned about the impact on freelance work in the next 24 months with no honest and equitable solutions being discussed. 

#AI #dataanalytics #foodtech #jobloss #MIT

This is not an easy process. We will educate and build our own regional supply chains and/or squeeze legacy producers that fail to find the means to change because of a culture and economy that wants us to live shorter lives than the past generation. I’ve joined the advisory board for US Resiliency and regional food centers. The USDA has just announced the finalists for twelve new USDA Regional Food Business Centers, along with $420 million in funding to strengthen the food supply chain infrastructure. I’m truly hoping this development and follow on funding for farmers can shift technology and data tools for the entire agricultural industry as a whole. Congratulations to all of the finalists for the USDA Regional Food Business Centers.

It feels good to be joining an incredibly passionate group of folks from lots of backgrounds that believe the impact of data and digital solutions in farming. 

I am energized by the work so many are doing on the ground to support small farmers and value-added producers. And the financial support the USDA is giving out to finally support underserved farmers, and while there is billions more that needs to be spent to repair our communities and our food, I truly believe that this funding will have a huge impact on the agricultural industry in bringing in more modern systems. As we continue to explore new ways to use data and digital solutions to support farming, the program will create new and expanded local market opportunities which will improve incomes and opportunities. 
@usdagov.  I’m looking forward  to advising the region and see @journeyfoods work on value-added digitization. 

Finally, I created these images with #ai and believe we need to see younger, more diverse expressions of farmers as most farms are being consolidated and majority of farm managers are aging.

Raise your hand if you shop at Aldi’s 🖐️ 
Let’s talk about the captivating history of Aldi grocery store, European food laws on food dye, and the intriguing connection between Aldi and Trader Joe’s ownership. Plus, learn why Aldi’s brand products are free from food dyes.

Did you know that Aldi’s roots date back to 1946 in Germany? It started as a small store in Essen and has since become a global discount supermarket chain, revolutionizing the way we shop.

European food laws play a crucial role in regulating food dyes. The European Union has stringent guidelines that prioritize consumer safety and product quality, subjecting food additives to rigorous testing and approval processes.

Here’s where it gets interesting! Trader Joe’s and Aldi have a special connection. The Albrecht family, founders of Aldi, split their business in the 1960s, giving rise to Aldi Nord and Aldi Süd. Theo Albrecht, who owned Aldi Süd, went on to establish Trader Joe’s in the United States.

Now, let’s talk about Aldi’s commitment to your well-being. Aldi’s brand products stand out because they are free from food dyes. By avoiding artificial additives, including food dyes, Aldi provides you with healthier and more natural choices. But Aldis has been axed in historically low-income and diverse neighborhoods in the US. It’s time for more brands to push for shelf-space and more millennials to request nearby stores. 

#Aldis #FoodScience #TraderJoes #NoFoodDyes  #Transparency #fooddye

An Independence Day Message video from Joaquin Orozco.
My message: On this day are we remembering the essence of true independence. Our indigenous wisdom teaches us the importance of mindfulness in our choices. Drugs, food, and medicinals are not commodities; they are gifts from the Earth. Let us honor them with respect, seeking them with intention during our celebrations — or they harm our intent.

Independence from those on the other side of the pond  and right below our feet keeps us closer to resilience and wisdom. We only should glorify independence from exploitation of the land, not the thriving in unison.

The land is our foundation and kept whole the most indigenous and wisest of the lands, deserving our care and protection. It is not a commodity to exploit but a sacred entity. Let us reclaim our role as stewards of the earth.

On this day, let us honor our ancestors, medicines, food, culture, and land. With mindfulness, we regain independence from controlling systems. Happy Independence Day!
#happyindependenceday #herbals #medicine #foodculture #landwisdom #indigenous #capitalism #creativehealing

Lunchables were always convenient and fun but they are from from the soul of what our kids should be consuming every day at school. And there’s growing complexity. The presence of Lunchables reflects far-reaching decisions shaped by the food industry's influence in Washington, exposing weaknesses in federal standards. 

Outdated regulations have fueled America's childhood obesity crisis, resulting in a fourfold increase in child obesity since the 1970s. Recent discussions on school nutrition, more than a decade after the last overhaul, entail the USDA's proposal for stricter sodium and sugar limits by 2025. However, opposition from industry stakeholders, congressional Republicans, and the School Nutrition Association highlights the ongoing struggle to harmonize child health with food industry profits. 

The food industry's escalating interest in the school lunch market is driven by the potential for long-term customer loyalty, while the nutritional integrity of school meals remains a complex issue. School lunches' role in the health crisis in the U.S., which impacts life expectancy and results in rising rates of fatty liver disease among children, underscores the urgency of addressing the chronic illness epidemic. 

The industry's pervasive advertising of highly processed foods, especially appealing to children, coupled with federal resistance to dietary improvements, underscores the United States' battle with childhood obesity. The School Nutrition Association's close financial ties with the food industry raise questions about the organization's autonomy, further complicating the quest for healthier school meals. The U.S. finds itself at a critical juncture, torn between the need for stringent school nutrition standards, industry interests, and providing nutritious meals that cater to students' tastes.

#lunchables #nutrition #teachers #schoollunch #education #chile #usda #lunch #marionnestle #foodtank

Keep eating your collard greens. In a country rife with problems we always need hope for some more superheroes, and that will be collard greens. This holiday season, the trends on the table tell a tale of economic shifts. Challah Bread, once a staple, now comes at a higher cost per pound, and the savory indulgence of Lamb Rib is accompanied by a heftier price tag. Pomegranates, once a symbol of abundance, are now a luxury, and the convenience of pistachios is tempered by an inflated cost. Amidst the festivities, even the classic Eggnog demands a premium. Yet, amidst these shifts, Tofu remains a beacon of affordability, reminding us that some culinary joys still stand resilient against economic challenges when supplemented by lobbyists and an upside down farm system. Collard Greens, once a budget-friendly choice, continue to provide a wise investment in nutrient-density and ease. As Octavia wisely puts it, prices are gonna keep going up and not down. Stay green and make your own bread. 

A holiday collection. Which is most shocking? We have hundreds loaded. Which would you like to see in a visual? 

Food inflation is the second biggest inflationary category today, and will continue to be a problem for months and years to come. Let’s keep an Olivia eye on
‘em.

A few notes 
“It is so important that we fight for the future, get dirty, get experimental” @adriennemareebrown . I envision a 2024 where we are all scientists, and not just any old scientists but scientists that have an imagination and trust as stronger than theories and reckless accolades of the past. I sat down with @sineadbovell to discuss why there’s a little scientist in all of us and how she views the most groundbreaking research happening today. 

When we are all scientists at the table, whether that be one of art, experience, hood healing, we will ask more questions and seek more answers that are designed for us and by the ones we love most. if we cannot find it in ourselves to step into these roles, we must at least make the tables a little more symbiotic, right? We can humbly call on somebody from a different jar and concoct a better future. 

Why, in this mosaics of human experience, do we not prioritize the voices intimately connected, and often the direct subjects under study?  I was happy to open up more wisdom on this recently with jumping deeper into @adriennemareebrown words : The traditional structure of scientific inquiry, as Adrienne Marie Brown aptly points out in “Emergent Strategy,” often isolates science from political and personal perspectives. However, embracing a more inclusive approach allows for a harmonious integration of diverse worldviews, acknowledging the interconnectedness of science and culture. Very opposite to how science is taught. But if the scientists do not currently represent us all, then how can we all benefit? It’s time for a paradigm shift 

The question emerges: can we all be scientists? Brown’s proposition challenges the prevailing hierarchy of scientific investigation, urging us to reconsider the ethical dimensions of our pursuits. Science, when harnessed as a force for minimizing suffering and amplifying joy, transcends the boundaries of conventional thinking…

#weareallscientists #sineadbovell #adriennemariebrown #adultsciencefair
